Ooh, right, because each character _is_ a wrapper, and multiple colons in the same fragment are not allowed. That also answers my [question](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/30197#discussion_r1668972900) about why we iterate in reverse, and why this implementation is correct.

This is probably fairly obvious to people familiar with Miniscript, but feel free to adopt this docstring anyway if it's helpful:

```cpp
    auto count{0};
    // A wrapper is a single character followed by a colon, e.g. `t:`.
    // The colon is dropped between subsequent wrappers; e.g. `dv:` is
    // the `d` wrapper applied to the `v:` wrapper. For that reason, we
    // iterate in reverse and start counting when a colon is found until
    // the start of the fragment is reached.
    for (const auto ch: reverse_iterate(buff)) {
        if (ch == ':') {
            ++count;
        } else if (ch == ',' || ch == '(' || ch == '{') {
            count = 0;  // start of fragment
        } else if (count > 0 && ++count > max_wrappers) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
```

